437
00:29:22,920 --> 00:29:27,160
That might be $20,000 well spent in the context of a Worldcon budget.

438
00:29:27,160 --> 00:29:28,180
Yeah, that's fair.

439
00:29:28,180 --> 00:29:29,200
And it might grow.

440
00:29:29,200 --> 00:29:36,880
And I assume that that's not, that $20,000 is basically the same whether you have 200 or 2,000 people at the meeting.

441
00:29:37,120 --> 00:29:45,260
The other consideration is, I think if you are a Worldcon that has its stuff together, you might decide to do this because you think it's the right thing to do.

442
00:29:45,260 --> 00:29:56,880
My worry is that the more obstacles there are to seeing this as clearly a direct win over holding an in-person one, the more likely it is that Worldcon will not do it.

443
00:29:56,880 --> 00:30:07,400
And so, for instance, Montreal, which I suspect will be relatively poorly attended and does not seem to be a very together convention, I can very much imagine them not doing this.

444
00:30:07,400 --> 00:30:11,620
Because they might not have the money and they might not have, you know, the spoons.

445
00:30:11,620 --> 00:30:15,580
And Tammy did ask Montreal on Blue Sky.

446
00:30:15,580 --> 00:30:19,700
And as far as I know, Montreal has not commented.

447
00:30:19,880 --> 00:30:30,940
Two things to say, which is, one, I'm not assuming Montreal will be small because I think there might be people who have chosen not to go to US Worldcons for a couple of years who quite like the idea of going to Worldcon again.

448
00:30:30,940 --> 00:30:33,640
And also, we don't necessarily know it will be a financial decision.

449
00:30:33,640 --> 00:30:45,360
It might be they have a head and parliamentary set up for the WUSFUS meeting in 2027, would prefer to do an in-person one and decide they're going to do an in-person one regardless of money.

450
00:30:45,360 --> 00:30:48,520
So that might not be the only criteria that they use to decide.

451
00:30:48,960 --> 00:30:49,900
I think there's a lot of things in it.

452
00:30:49,900 --> 00:30:54,540
Jesse did note, I love the idea of showing voting results like everyone votes, though.

453
00:30:54,540 --> 00:30:58,700
I love the idea of having everyone at the meeting create a custom avatar and animating them actually voting.

454
00:30:58,700 --> 00:31:01,100
Maybe we can get sponsored by a visual effects company.

455
00:31:01,100 --> 00:31:06,700
And if there's ever another ConZealand, we could get Weta to do it.

456
00:31:06,700 --> 00:31:07,300
Right?

457
00:31:07,300 --> 00:31:08,960
And that would be dope.

458
00:31:08,960 --> 00:31:12,200
I want Weta to do all our avatars.

459
00:31:12,200 --> 00:31:13,080
Yes.

460
00:31:13,080 --> 00:31:16,900
They should just let you pick through the Weta-like past library.

461
00:31:17,260 --> 00:31:20,320
So, you know, you can be an Ent or an Orc or...

462
00:31:20,320 --> 00:31:21,180
Bagsy Treebeard.

463
00:31:21,180 --> 00:31:22,440
Could I be Aragorn?

464
00:31:22,440 --> 00:31:25,620
Yeah, they probably did make a fully CGI Aragorn, didn't they?

465
00:31:25,620 --> 00:31:26,880
100%.

466
00:31:26,880 --> 00:31:27,860
I don't know.

467
00:31:27,860 --> 00:31:29,540
Because it was in 2002.

468
00:31:29,540 --> 00:31:33,520
They did less CGI than you think.

469
00:31:33,520 --> 00:31:39,600
Lots of forced perspective and people on stilts and things like that.

470
00:31:39,600 --> 00:31:40,240
Yeah.

471
00:31:40,580 --> 00:31:41,940
Okay, so what do we want to talk about next?

472
00:31:41,940 --> 00:31:49,640
I think we should probably mention that F12, which was introducing the Speculative Poetry Hugo Award, passed.

473
00:31:49,640 --> 00:31:51,860
So we'll be down for ratification in Los Angeles.

474
00:31:51,860 --> 00:31:58,260
So if you either want or don't want a Speculative Poetry Hugo, you should look out for that next year.

475
00:31:58,500 --> 00:32:05,880
I think this was probably a year early because it would have been nice to at least see how many people vote and what happens this year before it was introduced.

476
00:32:05,880 --> 00:32:08,700
But it's very hard to argue against a Hugo category.

477
00:32:08,700 --> 00:32:12,900
Because if you argue against a particular Hugo category, it's because you don't like poets or something.

478
00:32:12,900 --> 00:32:20,880
I think if I were a Worldcon, this would make me think really hard about whether to do a special one off Hugo.

479
00:32:20,880 --> 00:32:29,820
Because if I think there is a chance that people are going to use that to try and get another permanent Hugo on, and I'm in charge of whether or not to do the special one, I'm just not going to do it.

480
00:32:29,820 --> 00:32:37,780
I think we have other Hugo categories where we struggle to find really good finalists.

481
00:32:37,780 --> 00:32:41,640
And I think this is even more at risk of that.

482
00:32:41,640 --> 00:32:44,880
I feel we haven't really thought necessarily thought it through.

483
00:32:44,880 --> 00:32:46,260
I don't hate poets.

484
00:32:46,260 --> 00:32:57,020
Maybe I should introduce a one in one out system for the Hugo so that if you propose a new Hugo, you also have to simultaneously propose the one we're going to scrap to let it in.

485
00:32:57,020 --> 00:32:58,800
That wouldn't be controversial, would it?

486
00:32:58,800 --> 00:33:04,040
I mean, I think what we know now is that we ran Best Poem as a category this year.

487
00:33:04,040 --> 00:33:07,600
It got six nominees that are totally fine.

488
00:33:07,600 --> 00:33:16,680
We know that nomination numbers in this category for those six were low, but not so low that it stands out massively compared to other categories.

489
00:33:16,680 --> 00:33:26,440
And so, you know, if you'd run it as a special Hugo and you said, look, we got 27 nominations for 27 different things, then that would be an obvious case of, all right, well, there's no appetite for this.

490
00:33:26,660 --> 00:33:31,840
So you do have some information as to what Hugo voters think about a poetry category.

491
00:33:31,900 --> 00:33:41,520
I just think it would be nice to have seen the whole process through and to know kind of like the long tail of the nominations and to see how many people actually vote and what they vote for before we start saying it should be a permanent category.

492
00:33:41,520 --> 00:33:43,720
But I can understand it's two years to ratification.

493
00:33:44,020 --> 00:33:52,400
Then the idea here is it would be first, it would take effect at the end of 2026 and you could have one in 2027 and they may not wish to wait till 2028 for, sorry, Best Poem Hugo.

494
00:33:52,800 --> 00:33:58,200
But I just want to see a bit more like let's do one cycle of it and show it's actually a viable category.

495
00:33:58,200 --> 00:33:59,320
It's interesting, right?

496
00:33:59,320 --> 00:34:11,880
Because if LA follows suit after Glasgow and Seattle with doing the consultative votes on ratifications, it'll be interesting to see what the wider membership thinks of the idea of a Best Poem Hugo.

497
00:34:12,040 --> 00:34:19,840
And it will also be interesting to see what the number of people who vote either way is because I suspect most people are ambivalent.

498
00:34:19,840 --> 00:34:22,940
Maybe that's unfair, but that is my suspicion.

499
00:34:23,360 --> 00:34:27,740
I mean, I kind of feel that this is the same for like most Hugo votes.

500
00:34:27,740 --> 00:34:42,160
I can't remember what year it was there was a proposal to remove Best Semi-Prozine, but I suspect one of the highly attended votes from one of the business meetings was a removing Best Semi-Prozine one.

501
00:34:42,160 --> 00:34:47,080
Because then you can get lots of people to turn up and say, we support Semi-Prozine Hugo, we don't want to remove it.

502
00:34:47,480 --> 00:34:58,940
So there's probably like some people who are super in favour, some people who are super against, and then a lot of people who are basically ambivalent on any particular Hugo, I think, apart from maybe Best Novel, where we know lots of people always nominate and vote.

503
00:34:58,940 --> 00:35:03,120
And so then it's just basically impossible to ever remove Hugo.

504
00:35:03,120 --> 00:35:05,380
Do we have anything else on poetry?

505
00:35:05,380 --> 00:35:06,260
No.

506
00:35:06,260 --> 00:35:08,480
Sorry, I just wanted to do that in haiku.

507
00:35:08,480 --> 00:35:10,620
I had no pithy comment in haiku.

508
00:35:10,620 --> 00:35:11,840
I clearly need to plan.

509
00:35:11,840 --> 00:35:16,340
The other thing that happened is that the NASFIC has gone.

510
00:35:16,500 --> 00:35:18,300
It has been removed from the constitution.

511
00:35:18,300 --> 00:35:23,180
Other than the trademark will still be maintained.

512
00:35:23,180 --> 00:35:33,000
Although I am sceptical, I don't know how well that will work if we're no longer holding NASFICS, because my understanding is that to keep a trademark, you actually have to show that you're using the trademark.

513
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:33,620
So we'll see.

514
00:35:33,620 --> 00:35:34,420
We'll see how that goes.

515
00:35:34,420 --> 00:35:40,040
But that basically means that the de facto National American Convention is now DragonCon.

516
00:35:40,040 --> 00:35:43,860
Why DragonCon rather than San Diego Comic Con?

517
00:35:43,860 --> 00:35:46,260
Because San Diego Comic Con is a comics convention.

518
00:35:46,260 --> 00:35:47,480
Why not GenCon?

519
00:35:47,480 --> 00:35:52,680
Well, I think what we're saying is it's maybe not as clear cut as John is making it out.

520
00:35:53,200 --> 00:35:58,340
I want to say something here, which is that I went to my first World Con in 1987, which is a long, long time ago.

521
00:35:58,780 --> 00:36:10,580
And during that convention, when people were trying to explain the business meeting to me and my head was exploding, I said, why is the NASFIC in the WUSFUS Constitution?

522
00:36:10,580 --> 00:36:11,960
This makes no sense whatsoever.

523
00:36:12,080 --> 00:36:18,400
I mean, I didn't say that in those words because I did not know things like WUSFUS at that point or possibly even Constitution.

524
00:36:18,400 --> 00:36:33,880
But I did think it was quite strange that quite a lot about the way in which World Con operates in North America was included in this Constitution of something which I thought erroneously was a World Convention, which it now is.

525
00:36:34,120 --> 00:36:35,900
All those only a few years later.

526
00:36:35,900 --> 00:36:42,780
In 87, did you have like that weird zonal bidding system where it kind of officially bounced around outside the US once every four years or something?

527
00:36:42,780 --> 00:36:43,020
Yeah.

528
00:36:43,020 --> 00:36:46,340
So I think it had moved away from that.

529
00:36:46,460 --> 00:36:52,060
I think you could be outside any of the years, but this is going into history.

530
00:36:52,060 --> 00:37:06,300
But yes, it rotated within the United States and the people in the Wimpy Zone, which is the middle of the country, complained that outside US bids were targeting them.

531
00:37:06,300 --> 00:37:11,720
So in the wider context of what's happening in fan run conventions in the United States.

532
00:37:11,720 --> 00:37:19,720
So the only current US World Con bid is Texas in 2031, which is being headed up by Sarah Felix.

533
00:37:19,720 --> 00:37:20,880
And that's quite a long way in the future.

534
00:37:20,880 --> 00:37:21,780
So we'll see what happens.

535
00:37:21,780 --> 00:37:26,580
There are no currently announced World Con bids in the USA.

536
00:37:26,580 --> 00:37:30,420
Other than that, Westacon has come to an end.

537
00:37:30,420 --> 00:37:35,200
So those who don't know, Westacon is a West Coast convention, which has been running for about 50 years.

538
00:37:35,200 --> 00:37:39,060
And that has come to an end because there are not enough people who want to run Westacons.

539
00:37:39,060 --> 00:37:45,160
WizCon has stopped running in person because, again, they have not got enough volunteers to run a convention.

540
00:37:45,160 --> 00:37:52,400
Gallifrey One has come to an end because the people who run that have decided that they can no longer run it.

541
00:37:52,400 --> 00:37:56,100
And they're letting Showmasters events run a commercial replacement.

542
00:37:56,880 --> 00:38:02,220
Geek Girl Con and Penguin Con have both had real problems.

543
00:38:02,220 --> 00:38:07,560
Penguin Con is coming back, but Geek Girl Con still doesn't know if it's going to be able to.

544
00:38:07,560 --> 00:38:15,840
And Aresia, Bay Con, Boscon, Lost Con, those are all other North American fan run conventions, all of which appear also to be struggling.

545
00:38:15,840 --> 00:38:21,620
And I think it's worth noting that we appear to be going from that we've put the world in World Con.

546
00:38:21,920 --> 00:38:27,580
We are now going to need the world to run all of the World Cons because it appears the US is not going to.

547
00:38:27,580 --> 00:38:29,360
Where do we go from here?

548
00:38:29,360 --> 00:38:40,100
So if we assume we can get two a decade from the UK and Ireland and we assume we can get one or two a decade from Canada, one from the Antipodes, that leaves five.

549
00:38:40,100 --> 00:38:42,640
Where do we get the other five from?

550
00:38:42,640 --> 00:38:43,720
That's my question.

551
00:38:43,720 --> 00:38:45,500
Run them once every two years?

552
00:38:45,500 --> 00:38:46,560
What, in the UK?

553
00:38:47,140 --> 00:38:47,740
No, no, no.

554
00:38:47,740 --> 00:38:48,480
In general.

555
00:38:48,480 --> 00:38:49,240
In overall.

556
00:38:49,240 --> 00:38:50,840
Stop having one every year.

557
00:38:50,840 --> 00:38:52,200
So let it die.

558
00:38:52,200 --> 00:38:54,300
Or begin the decline, is the answer.

559
00:38:54,300 --> 00:38:59,780
So I think the thing we see in the UK is that World Cons have a huge effect on volunteering.

560
00:38:59,780 --> 00:39:06,440
So Lung Con 3 and Glasgow 2024 both brought large numbers of volunteers and people into the community.

561
00:39:06,440 --> 00:39:09,400
And without those events, you don't get those injections.

562
00:39:09,740 --> 00:39:20,420
And I think that is a problem if we don't have as many because it means we get fewer injections of people into science fiction fandom and into con running.

563
00:39:20,420 --> 00:39:23,140
Do we think that's probably true or do we think that's off base?

564
00:39:23,140 --> 00:39:40,100
I think we've been very fortunate with the last three UK and Irish World Cons in that the way they were conceived and run was a way that encouraged and supported a lot of both volunteers and new attendees to come along.

565
00:39:40,100 --> 00:39:48,280
I don't think all World Cons do that to the extent that Lung Con Dublin 2019 and Glasgow 2024 did.

566
00:39:48,280 --> 00:39:49,860
I think they were exceptional.

567
00:39:50,320 --> 00:39:52,120
I think 2005 did as well though, right?

568
00:39:52,120 --> 00:39:55,500
I grant you 1980 whatever it was didn't.

569
00:39:55,500 --> 00:39:58,000
And I don't know much about 95.

570
00:39:58,000 --> 00:39:59,660
1987 didn't.

571
00:39:59,660 --> 00:40:04,060
1987 and 1995 burnt their volunteers out.

572
00:40:04,060 --> 00:40:06,860
But obviously both of them brought a lot of people into fandom.

573
00:40:06,860 --> 00:40:09,460
So there's two different things.

574
00:40:09,460 --> 00:40:14,080
There's bringing in new volunteers, which I think the last three conventions have been very, very good at.

575
00:40:14,080 --> 00:40:19,760
And I think there's bringing people into fandom more generally, which I think all UK and Irish World Cons will do.

576
00:40:20,000 --> 00:40:25,540
The number of people who worked on a convention for the first time at those three conventions was enormous.

577
00:40:25,540 --> 00:40:26,440
And that's great.

578
00:40:26,440 --> 00:40:30,000
I'm just not sure I have that much to add on this one.

579
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:34,540
I don't know enough about the American scene.

580
00:40:35,040 --> 00:40:40,000
I don't know how much like American World Cons do.

581
00:40:40,000 --> 00:40:48,820
Is it that like every time you have a Chicago one, the same people have been running bits of Chicago ones or someone comes in at one Chicago one and then runs a big part in the next one?

582
00:40:48,820 --> 00:40:53,920
Or is it actually completely national and people are running divisions at Seattle who ran stuff at Chicago?

583
00:40:54,020 --> 00:41:01,440
Or is it actually that people are running divisions at Seattle who came in through Glasgow or who came in through London or Dublin?

584
00:41:01,440 --> 00:41:03,740
So I don't quite know how our mix is.

585
00:41:03,740 --> 00:41:05,980
I think the answer is, is yes.

586
00:41:05,980 --> 00:41:08,180
I was going to say all of the above.

587
00:41:08,440 --> 00:41:08,740
Yeah.

588
00:41:08,740 --> 00:41:16,320
So like, so there are people running divisions at LA who came up through Glasgow, for instance.

589
00:41:16,320 --> 00:41:17,580
I know this to be true.

590
00:41:17,740 --> 00:41:23,760
So I think this isn't even necessarily only a question in the States, right?

591
00:41:23,760 --> 00:41:28,720
Like, I think, I think World Con as a thing, people work on World Cons and then do work on other World Cons.

592
00:41:28,720 --> 00:41:30,860
And it's difficult to geographically gate that.

593
00:41:30,860 --> 00:41:38,040
But I also think that like, for instance, I know Glasgow social media was largely led by a team of people who were in Glasgow.

594
00:41:38,040 --> 00:41:45,440
And it's difficult to imagine those people would have spontaneously volunteered if there had never been a World Con in Glasgow, you know?

595
00:41:45,440 --> 00:41:46,340
Yeah, I think so.

596
00:41:46,340 --> 00:41:52,440
But I think it's not as simple as, well, I mean, I don't think we're saying it's simple as, but I don't think it's as simple as saying, you know, there are no bids for the US.

597
00:41:52,440 --> 00:41:56,420
So the US ones will fold and therefore the European ones will carry the torch.

598
00:41:56,420 --> 00:42:01,440
Because I think if the US ones go away, then the European ones will also be massively affected.

599
00:42:01,440 --> 00:42:02,380
Yes.

600
00:42:02,380 --> 00:42:04,420
This is largely my worry.

601
00:42:04,420 --> 00:42:10,360
I don't know how if you, we appear to be, and part of this is like global politics, right?

602
00:42:10,360 --> 00:42:15,200
So I do understand why the US doesn't have lots of people who are eagerly proposing bids right now.

603
00:42:15,200 --> 00:42:21,700
But at the same time, like, I do think it will be a problem for World Con more generally if all of the US World Con stop.

604
00:42:21,700 --> 00:42:25,800
And I don't think just going to every two years will be the solution.

605
00:42:25,800 --> 00:42:29,480
Because I think you will, you know, it's still lots of work.

606
00:42:29,920 --> 00:42:32,580
And like, it's not just the States that's having this problem.

607
00:42:32,580 --> 00:42:37,880
So since Con Zealand, New Zealand fandom seems to be having real problem with fan run conventions.

608
00:42:37,880 --> 00:42:42,020
Finland, I saw in Smof News, which I'd missed previously.

609
00:42:42,020 --> 00:42:43,800
So this is from a couple of months ago now.

610
00:42:43,800 --> 00:42:51,300
But FinCon announced that the 2025 FinCon will not happen because no one has volunteered to run it.

611
00:42:51,420 --> 00:42:59,380
And FinCon, kind of one of the reasons everyone was so excited about Helsinki was that FinCon was a really strong convention that had lots of attendees and a lot of energy.

612
00:42:59,380 --> 00:43:01,800
So that is also interesting.

613
00:43:01,800 --> 00:43:10,300
And like, anecdotally, Eastcons have been going around the same relatively small pool of people wanting to run them at a high level for a while.

614
00:43:10,300 --> 00:43:13,420
So, yeah, I don't think this is just an American problem.

615
00:43:13,420 --> 00:43:14,160
It's worrying.

616
00:43:14,260 --> 00:43:16,460
Alan Fleming and David Bamford are very new.

617
00:43:16,460 --> 00:43:17,080
Yep.

618
00:43:17,080 --> 00:43:22,940
But I think bringing in like two new people every decade might not be a sustainable trajectory.

619
00:43:22,940 --> 00:43:27,160
I think there's a lot of people at kind of area head level as well.

620
00:43:27,160 --> 00:43:28,260
And not lots, but some.

621
00:43:28,260 --> 00:43:29,640
I don't think you need a huge number.

622
00:43:29,640 --> 00:43:40,020
So this is all related to the general issue that the world is having that we had that volunteering is kind of falling off a cliff edge.

623
00:43:41,040 --> 00:43:50,040
Because a lot of, we did, we had a huge amount of volunteering when we created a society that underemployed quite a lot of people.

624
00:43:50,040 --> 00:43:53,360
And a lot of them did tons of volunteering in all sorts of different areas.

625
00:43:53,360 --> 00:43:58,020
Those people are now aging out of volunteering.

626
00:43:58,020 --> 00:44:03,680
And surprisingly enough, the generation below them are all working very hard.

627
00:44:04,340 --> 00:44:14,720
And it's not obvious where your next batch of volunteers are coming from, which means that a lot of the things that we rely on volunteers for are just kind of going to go away.

628
00:44:14,720 --> 00:44:24,400
And we'll either have to find paid models to do it or generate some new volunteers or find ways to have those things happen in a way that doesn't require volunteers to do them.

629
00:44:24,400 --> 00:44:27,080
Make all of those things happen.

630
00:44:27,220 --> 00:44:32,140
And for science fiction fandom in particular, UK fandom's a bit younger.

631
00:44:32,140 --> 00:44:36,580
UK fandom has always been a little bit younger than the US.

632
00:44:36,580 --> 00:44:39,240
So this is happening later in the UK.

633
00:44:39,240 --> 00:44:40,240
But it will still happen.

634
00:44:40,240 --> 00:44:42,960
Alison has written the cliff edge of volunteering in the show notes.

635
00:44:42,960 --> 00:44:49,120
And this seems to be all of the references I can find by Googling or otherwise searching that are British ones.

636
00:44:49,300 --> 00:44:51,480
So there seems to be a particular problem in Britain.

637
00:44:51,480 --> 00:45:01,100
I am not sure whether it explains what we're seeing in Finland and New Zealand and the States because I'm not Finnish or Kiwi or American.

638
00:45:01,100 --> 00:45:03,840
But yeah, it is a problem in the UK.

639
00:45:03,840 --> 00:45:13,480
